To read these tables:

  1. We infused the media with metabolites from 19 Pseudonocardia lines that had been collected from 19 different ant colonies (A-S), plus a non-infused control media. There are potentially genetic differences among these vertically transmitted lineages, so we call them: Ps.strain

  2. We measured growth rates of 9 strains of Streptomyces (1,2,3,5,6,7,8,9,10) and 10 strains of Softbugs (11-20). These are potential invading strains on attine cuticles so we call them: Inv.strain.

  3. Each (19 * 19 =) 361 combinations of Ps.strain and Inv.strain was repeated 3 times for a total sample size of (361 * 3=) 1083 treatment inoculations (19 * 9 * 3 Streptomyces inoculations = 513; 19 * 10 * 3 = 570 Softbug inoculations), but some colonies could not be scored due to difficulties in reading colony area, leaving us with (207 + 256 =) 463 Streptomyces inoculations and (240 + 310 =) 550 Softbug inoculations 463 + 550 = 1013 treatment inoculations + (27 + 30 =) 57 Control inoculations = 1070 total inoculations

  4. Thus, the experiment is fully crossed but somewhat imbalanced at the end.

  5. (513 - 463 =) 50 Streptomyces inoculations and (570 - 550) = 20 Softbug inoculations could not be scored.

To read these boxplots:

The y-axis is the final area (cm2) of the colony inoculated onto the plate (the notional invader)

  1. Streptomyces colonies are generally bigger than non-producer colonies (i.e. Streptomyces are faster growers), on all media: control and Pseudonocardia-infused.

  2. The 19 Pseudonocardia colonies (Ps.strain) used to infuse the media can be usefully divided into two 16S genotypes (Ps1 n = 8, Ps2 n = 11). Growth rates of Streptomyces and soft_bugs appear lower on the Ps2 infusions (i.e.Ps2 appears to be a more effective inhibitor in general).

  3. There are fewer Control datapoints because this represents only one kind of media, whereas the Pseudonocardia (Ps1 and Ps2) treatments represent 19 colonies.

Start of analysis.

There are two potential random factors:

  1. Pseudonocardia strains: Ps.strain (19 levels: A-S)
  2. Invader strains: Inv.strain (19 levels: numbered 1-20, but no strain 4). 1-10 are Streptomyces strains (no strain 4), 11-20 are Softbug strains

There are 3 Plate replicates for each combination of Ps.strain and Inv.strain, and each of the 19 Inv.strains is tested against each Ps.strain. Some complexity: not all inoculations were scorable, so were omitted, and there is no strain 4 in the Streptomyces. This is a fully crossed but somewhat imbalanced experiment

There are 2 fixed factors:

  1. Pseuonocardia genotype: Ps.genotype (Ps1, Ps2).
  2. Invader type: Invader (softbugs, Streptomyces)

Finally, the response variable is:

  1. Mean colony area (cm2): Invasion.score

Construct a full model and test for correlated residuals in each of the potential random factors

M1 <- lm(Invasion.score~Invader*Ps.genotype, data=assay3)
E1 <- rstandard(M1)
plot(E1 ~ assay3$Ps.strain); abline(0,0) # A,D,K,P,S strains either mostly above or below 0, demonstrating correlated residuals for some strains

plot(E1 ~ assay3$Inv.strain); abline(0,0) # 7,10,13,15,18,19,20 either mostly above or below 0, demonstrating correlated residuals for some strains

rm(M1)
rm(E1)

Thus, we use a model with random factors

# with interaction effect
M1 <- lmer(Invasion.score ~ Invader * Ps.genotype + (1|Ps.strain/Plate) + (1|Inv.strain), data=assay3, REML = FALSE)
# without interaction effect
M2 <- lmer(Invasion.score ~ Invader + Ps.genotype + (1|Ps.strain/Plate) + (1|Inv.strain), data=assay3, REML = FALSE)

anova(M1, M2) # no significant interaction effect:  p = 0.2672
## Data: assay3
## Models:
## M2: Invasion.score ~ Invader + Ps.genotype + (1 | Ps.strain/Plate) + 
## M2:     (1 | Inv.strain)
## M1: Invasion.score ~ Invader * Ps.genotype + (1 | Ps.strain/Plate) + 
## M1:     (1 | Inv.strain)
##    Df     AIC     BIC logLik deviance  Chisq Chi Df Pr(>Chisq)
## M2  8 -560.73 -520.93 288.37  -576.73                         
## M1 10 -559.37 -509.62 289.69  -579.37 2.6394      2     0.2672
AIC(M1, M2) # AIC difference < 2, and anyway the model with the interaction effect (M1) has a slightly higher AIC
##    df       AIC
## M1 10 -559.3702
## M2  8 -560.7307

Not surprisingly, there is no interaction effect

Random factors:

plot(assay3$Ps.strain, resid(M2), xlab="Ps.strain", ylab="Residuals"); abline(0,0)

plot(assay3$Inv.strain, resid(M2), xlab="Inv.strain", ylab="Residuals"); abline(0,0)

plot(assay3$Plate, resid(M2), xlab="Inv.strain", ylab="Residuals"); abline(0,0)

The corelated residuals have gone away, as expected.

Streptomyces grow more quickly than do the Softbugs (0.34240), and there is a growth-rate difference amongst the three media levels: Control, Ps1-infused, Ps2-infused. By eye and parameter value, it looks like the significant media effect is caused by Ps2, which we can test post-hoc.

Remove the Control level and test again for a significant effect of Ps.genotype

assay4 <- assay3 %>% dplyr::filter(Ps.genotype != "Control")
assay4$Ps.genotype <- fct_drop(assay4$Ps.genotype)

M5 <- lmer(Invasion.score ~ Invader + Ps.genotype + (1|Ps.strain/Plate) + (1|Inv.strain), data=assay4, REML = FALSE)
M6 <- lmer(Invasion.score ~ Invader + (1|Ps.strain/Plate) + (1|Inv.strain), data=assay4, REML = FALSE)
